You've got accountants becoming CPAs. You have financial analysts

01:08:11.000 --> 01:08:15.000
like the good ones are CFAs. Sorry, I'm saying all acronyms.

01:08:15.000 --> 01:08:19.000
Chartered financial analysts, lawyers, they have the bar.

01:08:19.000 --> 01:08:23.000
Everybody in all these other professions

01:08:23.000 --> 01:08:27.000
have some kind of professional organization, but we

01:08:27.000 --> 01:08:31.000
don't as data scientists.

01:08:31.000 --> 01:08:35.000
A lot of people trying to become a data scientist, they don't have an understanding

01:08:35.000 --> 01:08:39.000
of what the minimum requirements are,

01:08:39.000 --> 01:08:43.000
which I think would be useful for them.

01:08:43.000 --> 01:08:47.000
I'm curious if this is a sentiment that other people have or if I'm just

01:08:47.000 --> 01:08:51.000
going crazy. Maybe JJ can fix this one,

01:08:51.000 --> 01:08:55.000
Rachel.

01:08:55.000 --> 01:08:59.000
One of the things that all those professions or most of them have

01:08:59.000 --> 01:09:03.000
in common is their protected names. You can't call yourself

01:09:03.000 --> 01:09:07.000
a doctor. You can't call yourself a lawyer or an accountant unless you have that.

01:09:07.000 --> 01:09:11.000
Those are names that are regulated and protected. If you call yourself a doctor

01:09:11.000 --> 01:09:15.000
and you don't have that, then you're screwed.

01:09:15.000 --> 01:09:19.000
I don't think data scientists would be ever a protected name

01:09:19.000 --> 01:09:23.000
because scientists are not. I'm a biologist.

01:09:23.000 --> 01:09:27.000
I have a doctor title, but a lot of people that don't have a doctor title call themselves a biologist.

01:09:27.000 --> 01:09:31.000
I disagree with that, but I can't say

01:09:31.000 --> 01:09:35.000
anything to them. I think science in general is

01:09:35.000 --> 01:09:39.000
not really a protected name that people can have.

01:09:39.000 --> 01:09:43.000
I also wanted to mention, based on that, there is this

01:09:43.000 --> 01:09:47.000
data management organization.

01:09:47.000 --> 01:09:51.000
I'm going to send you. I'll put it in the chat. This is the only one

01:09:51.000 --> 01:09:55.000
that I ever found because I got a task to do a data management

01:09:55.000 --> 01:09:59.000
proposal that I disappeared into the ether.

01:09:59.000 --> 01:10:03.000
I don't know what happened with it, but because of that, I did a lot of research into these guys.

01:10:03.000 --> 01:10:07.000
This is the only one. There are schools that they

01:10:07.000 --> 01:10:11.000
pan out. To me, it was the only one. Maybe other people

01:10:11.000 --> 01:10:15.000
in the group know other ones. It seems to be the only quasi

01:10:15.000 --> 01:10:19.000
widely recognized certification in the field, although

01:10:19.000 --> 01:10:23.000
everybody and their brothers got a different certification program.

01:10:23.000 --> 01:10:27.000
You can do the certification for us. I have seen

01:10:27.000 --> 01:10:31.000
people ask for it. As data management becomes popular, this

01:10:31.000 --> 01:10:35.000
is being asked for on job profiles, but it's not specific for

01:10:35.000 --> 01:10:39.000
actually doing data science itself, but it's something related.

01:10:39.000 --> 01:10:43.000
One thing that has been frustrating for me is going

01:10:43.000 --> 01:10:47.000
through. I feel like a lot of people will take one course

01:10:47.000 --> 01:10:51.000
on Coursera, and they're like, I'm a data scientist. I'm like, hold up.

01:10:51.000 --> 01:10:55.000
What are some fundamentals you need to understand?

01:10:55.000 --> 01:10:59.000
P-hacking is a problem. Do you actually

01:10:59.000 --> 01:11:03.000
understand basic statistics?

01:11:03.000 --> 01:11:07.000
I get really frustrated as well.

01:11:07.000 --> 01:11:11.000
I'll check that out. Thank you.

01:11:11.000 --> 01:11:15.000
It's a great point, especially as people talk about reproducibility

01:11:15.000 --> 01:11:19.000
crisis and all that. The fact that there is

01:11:19.000 --> 01:11:23.000
no real certification.

01:11:23.000 --> 01:11:27.000
I was going to ask, actually,

01:11:27.000 --> 01:11:31.000
you were talking, this is sort of the technical skills. Do they have the

01:11:31.000 --> 01:11:35.000
stats and the understanding and certification on that? You were talking earlier about the business

01:11:35.000 --> 01:11:39.000
understanding and communication. I'm just

01:11:39.000 --> 01:11:43.000
wondering, how do you, I don't know, is that a hiring thing?

01:11:43.000 --> 01:11:47.000
What is that? How do you make sure you get people that not only do they know

01:11:47.000 --> 01:11:51.000
how to do the data science piece, but they have the business piece as well?

01:11:51.000 --> 01:11:55.000
When I'm hiring?

01:11:55.000 --> 01:11:59.000
You're building a team.

01:11:59.000 --> 01:12:03.000
When I've inherited teams,

01:12:03.000 --> 01:12:07.000
it becomes pretty clear who is interested

01:12:07.000 --> 01:12:11.000
in owning and really thinking. Unfortunately, a lot of people

01:12:11.000 --> 01:12:15.000
don't like to think. They generally leave

01:12:15.000 --> 01:12:19.000
if the expectations are high and their

01:12:19.000 --> 01:12:23.000
peers don't feel like they're pursuing it.

01:12:23.000 --> 01:12:27.000
Are you asking how do I make sure a new hire has those

01:12:27.000 --> 01:12:31.000
softer skills? I guess what I'm wondering is if

01:12:31.000 --> 01:12:35.000
that's a critical component of the success of the team,

01:12:35.000 --> 01:12:39.000
how do you make sure that the team has those skills? Hiring seems

01:12:39.000 --> 01:12:43.000
to be an obvious place, but if you already have a team, I guess

01:12:43.000 --> 01:12:47.000
what you're doing is you're setting expectations and they weed themselves out.

01:12:47.000 --> 01:12:51.000
That does work, actually. For the

01:12:51.000 --> 01:12:55.000
statistics and understanding what they're doing, I feel like that is an absolute

01:12:55.000 --> 01:12:59.000
fundamental. If you can't talk to somebody, that's a different problem.

01:12:59.000 --> 01:13:03.000
If you're making just bad analysis, it's going to destroy the team.

01:13:03.000 --> 01:13:07.000
The credibility is gone.

01:13:07.000 --> 01:13:11.000
My previous team, there was a range of who

01:13:11.000 --> 01:13:15.000
liked to do what. Because the

01:13:15.000 --> 01:13:19.000
technical skills were all solid, not everybody

01:13:19.000 --> 01:13:23.000
wants to talk to the business. The people that actually were good at it

01:13:23.000 --> 01:13:27.000
could take that role.

01:13:27.000 --> 01:13:31.000
In hiring, every time we're up to get a new

01:13:31.000 --> 01:13:35.000
person, the team would actually get together being like, what qualities

01:13:35.000 --> 01:13:39.000
are we lacking as a team? What do we need to really focus on

01:13:39.000 --> 01:13:43.000
to make sure this person is adding that value to our team?

01:13:43.000 --> 01:13:47.000
I don't think everybody is the same. I think you

01:13:47.000 --> 01:13:51.000
rely on each other. That's when it becomes powerful.

01:13:51.000 --> 01:13:55.000
Have you ever seen

01:13:55.000 --> 01:13:59.000
a project manager taking that kind of role, the communication

01:13:59.000 --> 01:14:03.000
with the business? Or is it usually someone from the team

01:14:03.000 --> 01:14:07.000
that wants to do that? My experience of project

01:14:07.000 --> 01:14:11.000
managers is not awesome. I've had one that I

01:14:11.000 --> 01:14:15.000
really liked.

01:14:15.000 --> 01:14:19.000
I'm sure there are some great ones. It's not that big, but we would just take on

01:14:19.000 --> 01:14:23.000
project management ourselves. Because generally, the project managers

01:14:23.000 --> 01:14:27.000
we had would turn more into task managers and not understand

01:14:27.000 --> 01:14:31.000
really the intricacies.

01:14:31.000 --> 01:14:35.000
I think not that long ago, somebody brought up their frustration

01:14:35.000 --> 01:14:39.000
with Scrum.

01:14:39.000 --> 01:14:43.000
Now we're doing stand-up meetings and

01:14:43.000 --> 01:14:47.000
it doesn't seem to be working for data science. I get

01:14:47.000 --> 01:14:51.000
that completely. Because data science and building a software

01:14:51.000 --> 01:14:55.000
product are so different, but everybody assumes the same.

01:14:55.000 --> 01:14:59.000
It feels to me like project management is generally more

01:14:59.000 --> 01:15:03.000
on a, this is the dedicated timeline and you're going to hit that.

01:15:03.000 --> 01:15:07.000
That's not really data science.

01:15:07.000 --> 01:15:11.000
I've not found project managers that useful.

01:15:11.000 --> 01:15:15.000
The one exception is they often will know

01:15:15.000 --> 01:15:19.000
more people initially at a company

01:15:19.000 --> 01:15:23.000
so they can help connect you with the person.

01:15:23.000 --> 01:15:27.000
Can I ask on the product managers and Scrum,

01:15:27.000 --> 01:15:31.000
because this was a big conversation for a while, that data science

01:15:31.000 --> 01:15:35.000
cannot be done in an agile way.

01:15:35.000 --> 01:15:39.000
It just doesn't work that way. There's a lot of people who argue that it can work

01:15:39.000 --> 01:15:43.000
in that way. Also, it comes back to the topic we mentioned before.

01:15:43.000 --> 01:15:47.000
I'm on the fence. It doesn't matter either way.

01:15:47.000 --> 01:15:51.000
What we mentioned before, reiteration and communication coming back and back.

01:15:51.000 --> 01:15:55.000
That would fit well with these kind of sprints and

01:15:55.000 --> 01:15:59.000
having a clear result and checking in, are we going in the right direction?

01:15:59.000 --> 01:16:03.000
Some people argue that actually it does work quite well.

01:16:03.000 --> 01:16:07.000
I think it can work well. I think people try to shove data science into

01:16:07.000 --> 01:16:11.000
how they create a

01:16:11.000 --> 01:16:15.000
software product.

01:16:15.000 --> 01:16:19.000
Shoving it into the box, it doesn't work.

01:16:19.000 --> 01:16:23.000
Data science, if we aren't actually agile, if we're not

01:16:23.000 --> 01:16:27.000
failing fast and making sure what we're doing still makes sense, will fail.

01:16:27.000 --> 01:16:31.000
What frustrates me is I'm like, hold on, the idea of

01:16:31.000 --> 01:16:35.000
agility isn't Scrum.

01:16:35.000 --> 01:16:39.000
It seems like people cross those wires.

01:16:39.000 --> 01:16:43.000
Yeah, you want to fail fast. Let's make sure we're doing things that are reasonable and not

01:16:43.000 --> 01:16:47.000
going down a rabbit hole and not talking to somebody for a month.

01:16:47.000 --> 01:16:51.000
The timeline thing can be tricky.

01:16:51.000 --> 01:16:55.000
I'm not sure about all that either. I still kind of prefer

01:16:55.000 --> 01:16:59.000
working on boards to

01:16:59.000 --> 01:17:03.000
the current Scrum. I don't know. I'm on the fence too.

01:17:03.000 --> 01:17:07.000
Rob B., I see you unmuted yourself. Did you have a

01:17:07.000 --> 01:17:11.000
final question?

01:17:11.000 --> 01:17:15.000
Thanks again for doing this, Tori.

01:17:15.000 --> 01:17:19.000
There's business skills.

01:17:19.000 --> 01:17:23.000
Then I guess one level deeper is there's

01:17:23.000 --> 01:17:27.000
industry level skills.

01:17:27.000 --> 01:17:31.000
You're a data scientist at a financial services company. You understand

01:17:31.000 --> 01:17:35.000
finance. Is that on the critical path

01:17:35.000 --> 01:17:39.000
for a hire on your team or in your organization?

01:17:39.000 --> 01:17:43.000
No. When I look

01:17:43.000 --> 01:17:47.000
at hires, I care if they can think logically. I do not

01:17:47.000 --> 01:17:51.000
care if they even have programming or if they

01:17:51.000 --> 01:17:55.000
understand the industry. I care about the way they think because

01:17:55.000 --> 01:17:59.000
I'm like, okay, if you think logically, hopefully they have

01:17:59.000 --> 01:18:03.000
programming. Most people now that are applying have programming.

01:18:03.000 --> 01:18:07.000
I can teach banking. I cannot teach logic.

01:18:07.000 --> 01:18:11.000
If you don't think that way, that's not going to work.

01:18:11.000 --> 01:18:15.000
Banking, I can teach.

01:18:15.000 --> 01:18:19.000
Discount cash flow, why bankers do things the way they are, that's simple compared

01:18:19.000 --> 01:18:23.000
to what I expect from a budding

01:18:23.000 --> 01:18:27.000
data scientist.

01:18:27.000 --> 01:18:31.000
There was one person I

01:18:31.000 --> 01:18:35.000
hired internally. Everybody else had

01:18:35.000 --> 01:18:39.000
it came from oceanography, physics,

01:18:39.000 --> 01:18:43.000
math, and none of them were banking.

01:18:43.000 --> 01:18:47.000
I actually found that really helpful because people see problems differently when they

01:18:47.000 --> 01:18:51.000
come from different industries. It's more of how do you tackle a problem?

01:18:51.000 --> 01:18:55.000
When you interview, how do you test

01:18:55.000 --> 01:18:59.000
for that skill? Can they think logically?

01:18:59.000 --> 01:19:03.000
I do actually use tests. We do have

01:19:03.000 --> 01:19:07.000
the regular talking to people.

01:19:07.000 --> 01:19:11.000
I usually give a couple different tests.

01:19:11.000 --> 01:19:15.000
One is a take home, like you have X amount of hours and here's

01:19:15.000 --> 01:19:19.000
some data. Do something with it. Give me a report. It's really open-ended.

01:19:19.000 --> 01:19:23.000
I found there's not

01:19:23.000 --> 01:19:27.000
so many ways you can solve it

01:19:27.000 --> 01:19:31.000
correctly. The wrong answers are just blatant.

01:19:31.000 --> 01:19:35.000
It's just obvious. The other thing that

01:19:35.000 --> 01:19:39.000
I don't know how to, we've been doing it online and it's weird to do

01:19:39.000 --> 01:19:43.000
it online, but it's nice to have somebody actually come in and try to do

01:19:43.000 --> 01:19:47.000
something live without internet. You're like, okay, here's a computer if

01:19:47.000 --> 01:19:51.000
you want. Here's your task you have to solve.

01:19:51.000 --> 01:19:55.000
Go for it. I don't really care if they solve it. I want to see how they

01:19:55.000 --> 01:19:59.000
go about it. I had one guy that could not for the life of him

01:19:59.000 --> 01:20:03.000
remember the package. I think he chose to use Python. He was like, I don't care

01:20:03.000 --> 01:20:07.000
what programming language you do. You have this task. He could not remember how

01:20:07.000 --> 01:20:11.000
to run a regression. On pen and paper,

01:20:11.000 --> 01:20:15.000
he figured it all out

01:20:15.000 --> 01:20:19.000
and then used his own algorithm and implemented it. He was one of

01:20:19.000 --> 01:20:23.000
the best hires I've ever hired. It was beautiful.

01:20:23.000 --> 01:20:27.000
Anyway, I try to pinpoint what are the skills

01:20:27.000 --> 01:20:31.000
and the thinking that I want to see. Can you demonstrate that?

01:20:31.000 --> 01:20:35.000
What I really want to avoid is the people that will

01:20:35.000 --> 01:20:39.000
be like, I'm going to throw all this data and use

01:20:39.000 --> 01:20:43.000
a convolutional neural network to solve something that really

01:20:43.000 --> 01:20:47.000
could be done with regular expressions.

01:20:47.000 --> 01:20:51.000
I've seen this. That's what I don't want.

01:20:51.000 --> 01:20:55.000
It's really obvious. It's a simple task.

01:20:55.000 --> 01:20:59.000
That's great. Do you ever ask

01:20:59.000 --> 01:21:03.000
them, because you touched on it before, asking them to explain

01:21:03.000 --> 01:21:07.000
to someone what they just did? If you then get people talking about

01:21:07.000 --> 01:21:11.000
here's the model and that piece as opposed to the value.

01:21:11.000 --> 01:21:15.000
Do you test for that as well?

01:21:15.000 --> 01:21:19.000
I played around with a couple things when somebody is doing a live coding or

01:21:19.000 --> 01:21:23.000
a live... Can you explain your thought process as you're going

01:21:23.000 --> 01:21:27.000
through this, which is really enlightening?

01:21:27.000 --> 01:21:31.000
I find it useful to see what type of questions

01:21:31.000 --> 01:21:35.000
people ask or how much will they persist?

01:21:35.000 --> 01:21:39.000
How much understanding

01:21:39.000 --> 01:21:43.000
are they trying to dig? That sounds

01:21:43.000 --> 01:21:47.000
subjective, but it becomes very apparent.

01:21:47.000 --> 01:21:51.000
Going off of Robert's question,

01:21:51.000 --> 01:21:55.000
do you find a lot of hires that do think logically

01:21:55.000 --> 01:21:59.000
but really only when it comes to the data science aspect?

01:21:59.000 --> 01:22:03.000
In the process of teaching them the banking and the business side,

01:22:03.000 --> 01:22:07.000
I guess a lot of these questions around what is the

01:22:07.000 --> 01:22:11.000
value of these things connecting with the business partners. I think I was thinking

01:22:11.000 --> 01:22:15.000
what Robert was is it might be helpful to find people who already

01:22:15.000 --> 01:22:19.000
have that sense of why this is valuable to the business.

01:22:19.000 --> 01:22:23.000
It sounds like you're more confident in your ability to just

01:22:23.000 --> 01:22:27.000
train them to do that and you want them to have those core skills instead.

01:22:27.000 --> 01:22:31.000
What is my question here? What is training

01:22:31.000 --> 01:22:35.000
them on the business look like to you?

01:22:35.000 --> 01:22:39.000
I always force people to actually have

01:22:39.000 --> 01:22:43.000
serious partnerships, but I think I understand your question because I've had a few employees

01:22:43.000 --> 01:22:47.000
where they get so excited about the modeling

01:22:47.000 --> 01:22:51.000
that they forget that actually we have to

01:22:51.000 --> 01:22:55.000
make value or there is no reason that we exist. We're

01:22:55.000 --> 01:22:59.000
just becoming an expense. I've had to have those

01:22:59.000 --> 01:23:03.000
conversations before. I know this is exciting, but there is a balance between

01:23:03.000 --> 01:23:07.000
figuring out a really cool way of doing this

01:23:07.000 --> 01:23:11.000
and giving real value without taking too much time.

01:23:11.000 --> 01:23:15.000
Those are conversations and depending on the person

01:23:15.000 --> 01:23:19.000
there are just people that would love to be in academia but are

01:23:19.000 --> 01:23:23.000
not.

01:23:23.000 --> 01:23:27.000
Some of the PhDs

01:23:27.000 --> 01:23:31.000
I have had more of that with.

01:23:31.000 --> 01:23:35.000
You've been in school forever. That is what you do.

01:23:35.000 --> 01:23:39.000
I had

01:23:39.000 --> 01:23:43.000
one other thought because we're still talking.

01:23:43.000 --> 01:23:47.000
Getting people to present their results is useful,

01:23:47.000 --> 01:23:51.000
but I've had to coach multiple people being like,

01:23:51.000 --> 01:23:55.000
remember who's in the audience. You're talking to the CEO. Is he going to care about this?

01:23:55.000 --> 01:23:59.000
No. He cares about his financials

01:23:59.000 --> 01:24:03.000
showing this, this, and this. How can you relate this back?

01:24:03.000 --> 01:24:07.000
Instead of spoon feeding it though, you've got to get them to actually

01:24:07.000 --> 01:24:11.000
understand how to do that, which takes time.

01:24:15.000 --> 01:24:19.000
I do have a meeting in five minutes, but I have three.

01:24:19.000 --> 01:24:23.000
I was going to say I'm waiting to see if someone else

01:24:23.000 --> 01:24:27.000
jumped in. Thank you so much, Tori.

01:24:27.000 --> 01:24:31.000
Thank you, guys. This was fun.

01:24:31.000 --> 01:24:35.000
This was a great session. I hope to see you next week, too.

